      "side": 1,
      "message": "This approach looks pretty nice!\n\nI feel like we\u0027re getting closer to the approach of gflags (https://github.com/gflags/gflags): we ask users to register globally accessible runtime variables on global initialization. If we think in this way, we will be interested in pulling more ideas from gflags, e.g.\n\n- Conflict detection: raise an error if multiple runtime variables with the same name are registered\n- Safe access: declare a global variable per runtime variable registration and allow accessing its value without repeating its name, eliminating chance of typo\n- Typed values: declare a type (e.g. int) and return a parsed value\n\nAlso, we should make sure runtime variables are not registered in the middle of execution. For example we don\u0027t want people to write code like this:\n\n func GetVar(ctx context.Context) string {\n   const varName \u003d \"foo.bar\"\n   testing.AddVar([]string{varName})\n   return testing.ContextVar(ctx, varName)\n }\n\nActually this issue also applies to existing registry methods (AddTest/AddFixture/AddService), but I\u0027m afraid that AddVar is more likely to be abused in this way.",
      "revId": "711e2b43c04f11dfd961b6febaa508a167f50fb1",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba"
    },
